[
    {
        "content": "<p>The space of steady state solutions of linear differential equations are Vector spaces, Hilbert spaces, etc.</p>\n<p>Is there some analog in category theory of \"specifications or conditions\" determining a category, rather than just a vector space?</p>",
        "id": 510512668,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1743967735
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I recently learned that the extensions of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span>, where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> is a group and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span> is an abelian group, organize to form a groupoid.</p>\n<p>So this is an example of situation where the solutions to some problem organize to form a category of some kind.</p>",
        "id": 510518430,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1743972163
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But probably you are mostly interested in examples relating to differential equations!</p>",
        "id": 510518643,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1743972309
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I suppose one could also pose a question: What are all the functors <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>:</mo><mi>C</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">:C \\to D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span>? Then the answers to that question organize to form a category.</p>",
        "id": 510518796,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1743972413
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>To try and get a category of solutions to a differential equation, I think you'd want some kind of notion of morphism between solutions of a given differential equation.</p>\n<p>(But I'm not sure what would work well for that!)</p>",
        "id": 510518918,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1743972508
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Examples like you have are good, I'm not sure what the appropriate generalizations should be. Algebraic equations specifying functions is the same sort of thing I'm curious about as well.</p>\n<p>Just maybe category theory has its own version in categorical language for example</p>",
        "id": 510519081,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1743972624
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You could imagine a functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>C</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F:C \\to D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span> where we think of the objects of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> as coming in different \"kinds\" depending on the isomorphism class of their image under <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span>. We could then ask: which objects are of kind <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>d</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">d \\in D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7335em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span>? (Which objects <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>c</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">c \\in C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> are such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>c</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>≅</mo><mi>d</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F(c) \\cong d</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span></span></span></span>?)</p>\n<p>We could then take the full subcategory of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> containing exactly the objects of kind <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">d</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 510519379,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1743972875
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(So then the question \"What are the objects of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> of kind <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">d</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span></span></span></span>?\" would have answers that organize to form a category.)</p>",
        "id": 510519430,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1743972934
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The category of algebras for a monad, or for an endofunctor, or the category of fixedpoints for an endofunctor, seem like reasonable examples to me.</p>",
        "id": 510521832,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1743974731
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thank you both!</p>",
        "id": 510522750,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1743975522
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you're interested in category theory and linear differential equations, you might (or on closer examination very possibly might <em>not</em>) want to learn about <a href=\"https://www.math.ntu.edu.tw/~dragon/Lecture%20Notes/D-modules/01-Introduction.pdf\">D-modules</a>.  The space of solutions of a system of linear partial differential equations defines a module of a certain noncommutative algebra helpfully called D.  Unfortunately most of the work on this is done in the holomorphic context, which is great if you like complex analysis or algebraic geometry, but not relevant otherwise.</p>\n<p>In this work, it's not as if a specific differential equation or a specific solution of a specific differential equation is a category.  Rather, there's a 'category of D-modules', and some D-modules come from systems of linear differential equations in the manner I just sketched.</p>",
        "id": 510533213,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1743984563
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'll admit I've struggled to break into algebraic geometry style thinking, but the specific recommendation to look at D-Modules might give me a foot hold.</p>\n<p>(Also an aside here, it's somewhat ironic to me that category theory is evidently useful for topology, a very squishy subject, and evidently useful for algebraic geometry; but <em>not</em> evidently useful for the \"happy medium\" of analysis. It's an odd state of affairs)</p>",
        "id": 510846199,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1744092844
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Algebraic topology largely about discrete structures - groups like <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span> or <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}/n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span> that remain when you 'mod out' by all the squishiness.   E.g. there's an interesting study of loops in topological spaces, but when we decree that two loops count as the same if there's a homotopy from one to the other, we're led to the concept of fundamental group.   </p>\n<p>They say a topologist can't tell the difference between a doughnut and a coffee cup.   But an <em>algebraic</em> topologist can't tell the difference between either of those and a circle! And they call this thing <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B \\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span> because it's the 'walking space with fundamental group <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span>'.</p>",
        "id": 511210171,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1744214154
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So, in algebraic geometry the structures involved are naturally somewhat rigid, while in algebraic topology we achieve rigidity by modding out by floppiness.</p>",
        "id": 511211509,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1744214464
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>...and in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>A</mi><mn>1</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A^1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> homotopy theory the algebraic geometers work really hard to reintroduce some floppiness so they can mod out by it.  (-:</p>",
        "id": 511249499,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1744227349
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, you could say they're trying to make algebraic geometry more like algebraic topology!</p>",
        "id": 511260579,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1744232042
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Not exactly what you're looking for, but the <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Fukaya%20category\">[[Fukaya category]]</a> of a symplectic manifold <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is defined using extremely heavy duty analysis! The objects in this category are lagrangian submanifolds, and arrows between lagrangians are intersection points, which doesn't sound so bad. But composition in this category comes from understanding a moduli space of maps from a disk with 3 punctures into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> satisfying a differential equation (\"J-holomorphicity\") and boundary conditions related to your lagrangians and intersection points.</p>",
        "id": 511322739,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Grossack (she/they)",
        "timestamp": 1744266021
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, and I guess I should mention these fukaya categories are <em>extremely</em> interesting and well studied! They're central in the statement of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homological_mirror_symmetry\">homological mirror symmetry</a>, which uses ideas from physics to make predictions about how algebraic geometry on one manifold should be related to analysis on another. This is made precise by letting \"algebraic geometry\" on one manifold mean \"derived category of sheaves\" and letting \"analysis\" on the mirror manifold mean \"fukaya category\". </p>\n<p>There's a LOT to say here, but most of it is fairly technical. It's definitely worth looking into, though, if you want analytically defined categories!</p>",
        "id": 511324123,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Grossack (she/they)",
        "timestamp": 1744266628
    }
]